text:
this sticker symbolizes who i based my vote off of: muslim individuals targeted by the travel ban. our kids’ education after republican senators refused to listen to our pleas and not confirm betsy devos. the charlottesville victims after the rise of white supremacy due to trump’s rhetoric. those who rely on obamacare for their health insurance and were worried about it being stripped away by a party with no true replacement plan. #metoo victims who didn’t see our government take a moral stand after brett kavanaugh was accused of sexual assault. the kids who were unjustly separated from their parents at the border. for all the jewish people who were shot dead in pittsburgh because of the rise of anti-semitism that resulted from the rise of white nationalism. every single victim from gun violence, where no common sense gun laws have passed because the nra funds too much money for our republican senators to take a stand. this all occurred after the house and senate were under the control of republicans. i know i sadly missed a few more incidents too.

it is time to flip the house and flip the senate. for our kids to study safely in school. for underrepresented communities to be better accounted for. and for competent leadership that understands our generation’s desire for more empathy and kindness in our nation’s politics. i have full confidence i will wake up tomorrow morning proud and content, unlike on november 8th, 2016. #ivoted #midterms2018 #bluewave #flipthehouse #flipthesenate #voteblue #votemccaskill #missourivoters #vote

text:
late lunch break: let’s talk about miscarriages and it’s effects on women...and men! 
the tragedy of miscarriage has traditionally been private (we don’t talk about it), an event grieved largely by the mother, on her own. this doesn’t mean that men don’t feel the pain as well (oh, they do!) but it is mostly grieved by women. people advise you that the sadness would grow less pronounced over time, especially following a successful pregnancy. not necessarily. 
studies show that the birth of a healthy baby does not resolve the mental health aftermath of miscarriage or stillbirth so it doesn’t just “go away”. some women may mourn for much longer than expected, even after the birth of a healthy child. that's also true for men! studies have found that men grieve over a miscarriage more than once thought and that the impact of miscarriage is often underestimated in both men and women. 
did you know that a woman who has a miscarriage is at risk for depression and anxiety symptoms in subsequent years (up to 15 years after). post miscarriage ptsd can also develop with symptoms like flashbacks, hyperarousal and intrusive thoughts - the woman may spend enormous amounts of emotional energy trying to explain why it happened. she often blames herself (even when it is inaccurate) to help make sense of it. she sometimes torments herself with guilt and blame - “if i hadn't gone to work that day” or ‘if i didn't argue with my spouse that morning”. this is a way of coping with the loss and it’s part of the grief process however we need to acknowledge the feelings and not just dismiss it. 
tips on coping with miscarriage(s): • first step is to admit your sadness. it’s okay to be sad. everything you’re feeling is normal. •don’t rush your “getting over it”. take your time. allow yourself off days to be sad just try not to stay there. •don’t let it put a strain on your relationship with your partner. you both need the emotional support for each other. remember he just lost his baby too. •therapy helps - group or individual. and when it starts to affect your everyday life, seek professional help! ❤️. #drsim #miscarriage #ptsd #grief #loss #depression #anxiety #psychmd #nycpsych #metoo

text:
#metoo 
in september,  i paid @cbtrn for a body paint photoshoot and i was sexually harassed during the process. some of the inappropriate physical contacts included: unnecessary message without consent, basically touching me everywhere especially lower body, spanking my butt, kissing my feet saying he has feet fetish on me, kissing me on my lip. he also used “arch more and show your clitoris” kind of language during photo shoot. 
i have talked with about 20 people who did photoshoot with him and about half have encountered similar experiences like massage without consent, being licked, being drove around for half an hour which usually only a 5-minute-drive to talk about his sex stories, private part being painted for excessive long time (you know there isn’t that much skin there).
i finally confronted with the photographer and he deflected the issue that he claimed to be suicidal and he needs to heal. doing art gave him the confidence to get back from surgery. i think this is just an invalid excuse. even though he promised to apologize in the public, he never did, so i think people should be informed about what is going on within this community. 
at the symposium arts & social justice breakfast: #metoo - what's next? hosted by @dance.nyc , i was shocked by how common the story was shared by dancers attended. so with support and love from friends and the community, i want to share some takeaways. 
1. artists, especially women in the theater/pole/aerial/circus/dance should support each other and be more open about sexual harassment. if this was brought up earlier, there wouldn’t be. no slut shaming and believe in women.
	2. our bodies are our craft. we trained so hard to perform but it does not mean that people can take advantage of our bodies during art creation even with partnerwork, photoshoot, body paint.
	3. go with a friend.
	4. draw the boundary and have everything written in contract. you can find a template about anti discrimination and sexual harassment below and i am also happy to share the one i used for private terms. 	5. other resources: do check out dance/nyc's growing list of sexual harassment resources
	6. keep up with the hard work, and share❤️

i finally confronted with the photographer and he deflected the issue that he claimed to be suicidal and he needs to heal. doing art gave him the confidence to get back from surgery. i think this is just an invalid excuse. even though he promised to apologize in the public, he never did, so i think people should be informed about what is going on within this community. 
at the symposium arts & social justice breakfast: #metoo - what's next? hosted by @dance.nyc , i was shocked by how common the story was shared by dancers attended. so with support and love from friends and the community, i want to share some takeaways. 
1. artists, especially women in the theater/pole/aerial/circus/dance should support each other and be more open about sexual harassment. if this was brought up earlier, there wouldn’t be. no slut shaming and believe in women.
	2. our bodies are our craft. we trained so hard to perform but it does not mean that people can take advantage of our bodies during art creation even with partnerwork, photoshoot, body paint.
	3. go with a friend.
	4. draw the boundary and have everything written in contract. you can find a template about anti discrimination and sexual harassment below and i am also happy to share the one i used for private terms. 	5. other resources: do check out dance/nyc's growing list of sexual harassment resources
	6. keep up with the hard work, and share❤️

text:
after moving to the dallas area, i caught myself in a senseless rage. i was looking for a job, and i was upset about how unprofessional a company was being. by upset, i mean violently upset. all because someone was being (in my mind) unprofessional.  it’s never really taken much to send me into a fiery rage that could last for hours or even days at a time. i just thought that was who i was. hyper-irritability (a form of hyper arousal) is a symptom of anxiety, and i’ve experienced it as long as i could remember.
_________________________________________
i have what’s known as complex post traumatic stress disorder (cptsd). it’s an anxiety disorder caused by repeated or prolonged trauma. only yah has helped me on this painful journey. i still have my struggles. when my triggers rear their ugly little heads, i use the a.m.e.n. system. it’s something i came up with a little over 3 years ago. full post is on the blog (#linkinbio).

text_retweet:
my friend is brave. my friend is bold. ▪
▪
▪
#repost @bossladycreates
• • • • •
asking for help is hard. i’m historically really bad at it. even when i know it’s what i need, even when it’s been offered to me on a silver platter with a cherry on top, i’ve rejected it in the past. and i know there are tons of layers to that: the cultural archetype of the “strong black woman” that i feel so deeply, not wanting to burden others with my problems, feeling that i should be able to handle this alone, the false notion that i don’t deserve it, the sting of the few times i’ve systematically sought it out and have been denied and denied and denied (the way the mental health profession has historically treated people of color and has personally treated me is another post for another time)... it’s a complex issue to be unpacked in multiple sessions with my therapist, but the point is that asking for help is really hard. it’s a question that is infinitely ongoing in respect to the survivor journey; and it is a question that, in and of itself, is the ultimate form of self care. •

realize that asking for help is not weakness. it’s not shameful, it’s not an admission of guilt- it’s knowing yourself and giving yourself what you need. this is what @serenawilliams meant when she said you have to put on your mask first. (y’all know!) and, after you have put on your mask, be generous with your help. pay it forward. you don’t have to be an influencer or a professional or a scholar to offer it. whether it’s sharing information and resources, telling your own story, or simply asking a fellow survivor “what do you need? how can i help?” saying “i’m believe you.” do it. then listen. dialogue. keep asking questions. don’t spout unsolicited advice or cliched affirmations. don’t assume that you can relate. (don’t assume anything.) every survivor’s needs are different. there’s no one-size-fits-all bandaid that can be slapped on this wound. active support rings so much truer than sympathetic apologies or thoughts and prayers. ✨ #help #survivor #survivorselfcare #believesurvivors #survivoradvocate #selfcare #metoo

asking for help is hard. i’m historically really bad at it. even when i know it’s what i need, even when it’s been offered to me on a silver platter with a cherry on top, i’ve rejected it in the past. and i know there are tons of layers to that: the cultural archetype of the “strong black woman” that i feel so deeply, not wanting to burden others with my problems, feeling that i should be able to handle this alone, the false notion that i don’t deserve it, the sting of the few times i’ve systematically sought it out and have been denied and denied and denied (the way the mental health profession has historically treated people of color and has personally treated me is another post for another time)... it’s a complex issue to be unpacked in multiple sessions with my therapist, but the point is that asking for help is really hard. it’s a question that is infinitely ongoing in respect to the survivor journey; and it is a question that, in and of itself, is the ultimate form of self care. •

realize that asking for help is not weakness. it’s not shameful, it’s not an admission of guilt- it’s knowing yourself and giving yourself what you need. this is what @serenawilliams meant when she said you have to put on your mask first. (y’all know!) and, after you have put on your mask, be generous with your help. pay it forward. you don’t have to be an influencer or a professional or a scholar to offer it. whether it’s sharing information and resources, telling your own story, or simply asking a fellow survivor “what do you need? how can i help?” saying “i’m believe you.” do it. then listen. dialogue. keep asking questions. don’t spout unsolicited advice or cliched affirmations. don’t assume that you can relate. (don’t assume anything.) every survivor’s needs are different. there’s no one-size-fits-all bandaid that can be slapped on this wound. active support rings so much truer than sympathetic apologies or thoughts and prayers. ✨ #help #survivor #survivorselfcare #believesurvivors #survivoradvocate #selfcare #metoo

text:
exposing the black gate keepers: the boule

membership to sigma pi phi is highly exclusive, the number only about 5,000. the organization is known as “the boule,” which means “a council of noblemen.” founded as an organization for professionals, sigma pi phi never established college chapters and eliminated undergraduate membership during its infant stages. however, sigma pi phi has historically had a congenial relationship with college black greek-letter organizations, as many members of sigma pi phi are members of both. sigma pi phi founder henry mckee minton and dr. martin luther king, jr. were both members of alpha phi alpha, while arthur ashe was a member of kappa alpha psi. vernon jordan, jr. is a member of omega psi phi. james weldon johnson was a member of phi beta sigma, as is civil rights leader and a member of congress john lewis (d-ga). members of sigma pi phi have provided leadership and service during the great depression, world war i, world war ii, the civil rights movement, and addressed social issues such as urban housing, and other economic, cultural, and political issues affecting people of african descent.

russ feingold is a former senator for wisconsin

.

text:
this text and photo was posted by @daralreayaen on twitter a year back. it was an account run by a former prisoner of dar al reaya, prisons for girls who run away from abuse or who dishonor their family in some way by disobeying. these places are located all over saudi. a woman i know was to one of these places recently. she confirms this is what women look like when going to the hospital or anywhere outside the institution- handcuffed and legcuffed and fully covered over the face. the photo is taken from isis but saudi dar al reaya prisons are similar and they are run by the government and the inmates are girls and women who simply disobeyed. i know it seems like a joke but i spoke to three witnesses who have been inside. phones are not allowed, no contact with the outside, except family members- the abusers the girl ran away from.
.
.
going to dar might be a womans only chance to escape abuse. but dont let the bastards grind you down- fight for your right, document your injuries from the guardian, get a lawyer before seeking help from a hospital and when they put you in dar demand to see that lawyer with name until they let you. many girls in there are stuck and wont get out unless the guardian takes them back or they are married off to another guardian, but those who fight hard and have a lawyer allready before going inside and the lawyer asks to see them... there might be a chance to make a case about the abuse you were put through by the guardian. but dont run away from the abuse, that will create a legal case against you! keep fighting in there to see the lawyer- never give up.

text:
“don’t worry, be happy” – the popular phrase is an auto-concept in our zeitgeist, and amba lamb uses it frequently. but, there are a “few” more things that can help sustain the concept. from the cayman island paradise, meet amba.
.
.
amba’s 36, in the industry for 22 years – it seems like those moments just flew by, but she’s made a critically awesome choice – move to a remote, high-end caribbean paradise, and the rest will come together. we love talking to those expat-transplants like amba about cayman – it’s more than surf and sun – they have a real opportunity to focus on sustainability and start small on their tiny island – make a difference in potentially larger areas using their beta test. amba is in love with travel, and apart from having a martini with her husband sam while looking at travel deals, she’s entertaining a discerning clientele at the island’s ritz carlton hotel as their beverage director, and an event planner for the annual “cayman cookout” by chef eric ripert – she gets to take these inspired elements from her travels, the people she meets, and creates new moments daily in her role; but how will you take the inspiration from iceland’s geo-thermal spas into the bar program? that’s – hopefully – her next trip. .
.
learning a new language, developing sustainable programming and acting as a bit of an “industry travel guide” is a nice combination for amba, and she brought these elements to life last year at the world class global finals in mexico city. .
.
so, once you arrive in grand cayman, look her up – she’ll be having a fictitious conversation with ernest hemingway at sting ray city. #minibarleadingladies

text: today, i voted. because the inability of some politicians to grasp the science behind climate change doesn’t make it any less real. because equality across genders, races, sexual orientations is most powerful in practice. because in the wealthiest country in the world, healthcare should be a right, not a privilege; access to food, water and shelter a necessity, not an “entitlement.” because women should be able to make decisions about their own bodies. because church and state should *actually* be separate. because americans working full time should not be living in poverty, and the wealthiest should not be given breaks they don’t need. because we should not fear being gunned down in the places we learn, worship and heal. because i believe survivors. because no human is illegal; diversity is one of our nation’s greatest strengths, not something used to stoke fear. because facts matter, science matters, the truth matters. because we should be building bridges, not walls. because love will always trump hate. today, i voted not just for change, but for progress. what did you vote for?

text:
as a woman, i am so grateful for women who come forward with their experiences of abuse (in particular sexual abuse) in order to protect other women.

christine is one of those women. in the second part of the podcast she talks about how the sexual abuse she experienced as a child and in college continues to effect her. she shares what her counselor told her that gave her the courage to prosecute her abuser, and a letter her abuser wrote to her from prison. christine talks about her belief in god and how that belief allows her to see the good - despite her situation. ❤️ link in bio to listen 👆

today is the day, friends. and there’s so much at stake. everything we know and love is on the line. our voice is our vote. speak up and vote like the life of this planet depends on it; because it does. vote like your life, the life of your friends and loved ones, and the life of your fellow americans depends on it; because they do. vote like you give a damn; because now more than ever before, you should. vote like the very existence of our democracy depends on it; because it does. although i am a proud democrat, this election isn’t about what side of the aisle we sit on. its not about blue or red. its not about us versus them. it’s so much bigger than that, friends. every accomplishment of those who came before us, is on the line. everything. that’s why we cannot afford to sit this one out. we cannot allow ourselves to be complacent. we cannot allow ourselves to take our right to vote for granted. we can vote for love, or we can vote for hate. we can vote for progress, or we can vote for regression. we can vote for unity, or we can vote for division. we can vote for equality, or we can vote for bigotry. the choice is ours. our future is literally in our hands. 
before the sun sets on this most important and consequential day, head down to your polling place and vote your heart out. be a part of something bigger than yourself. and remember; if history has taught us anything, it’s this: when we come together as passionate and united citizens, we are a force to be reckoned with. when we operate as ‘we the people,’ instead of ‘me the people,’ we are far more powerful than our elected officials will ever be. and today more than ever before, america is depending on us to stand up, speak up and show up on her behalf. let’s show her the greatness that lives inside of our hearts. ♥️♥️♥️ .

text:
making a complaint at work can sometimes feel like setting off fireworks... so if you are being harassed and make a complaint my top tip to you would be:
be clear about the solution.
it helps to know what you want the outcome of making the complaint to be. how could it be resolved from your perspective? do you require said behaviour to stop, do you need an apology, does the person require disciplinary action and is the incident a criminal matter? there is a whole spectrum of answers to this question, but it’s important to know what you want the solution to the report to be.

text:
america’s right to vote has shaped the world we all share.  while we haven’t always got it right we have led the world for decades and helped protect many that couldn’t protect themselves.  in dollars given we are the most generous country in the world, promoting human rights, democracy and education everywhere.  these ideals continue to influence our allies and trade partners across the world, and are a beacon to millions everywhere.

remember my friends, progress takes time, but we must make ourselves heard.  just 25 years ago the majority of people like me were abused and marginalized because we happened to be gay individuals.  not long before that black americans couldn’t share the same facilities as white americans and women were unable to cast a vote for their own beliefs.  those wrongs, at the time, were sanctioned by our government and despite those throughout history that have used fear to keep minds closed, we have progressed as a nation and a people because of the brave people standing up for equality and the votes that support them.

i voted early, but today i am a proud american because i was able to express my beliefs through my vote.  if you can see this i urge you to be a part of history that elects leaders that inspire us and that we can believe in and be proud of.  today let’s put the very best of each of us on the ballot!

text:
hey american friends — polls close at 8pm so go vote!! i know it’s raining. and you might feel like crap. or just be tried. or think “fk it, i don’t feel like it. my vote doesn’t matter anyway.” well... do it for the women across the world who can’t. for the little girl who dreams she could.

do it for the low-income women in texas who have to drive hours just to get healthcare they can afford from the only planned parenthood around because of a misguided political agenda.

do it because you don’t have complete control over your own reproductive organs in this country.

do it for the little girls who want to grow up with power over their own bodies.

do it because abigail adams was ridiculed when she wrote to her husband to “consider the ladies” when drafting our constitution.

do it because your voice matters, and your great grandma would’ve cried at the chance to make hers heard.

do it so the anita hill’s and dr. ford’s of the future will be respected and believed.

do it because it took 19 gd amendments to get here and we haven’t even had this right for 100 years yet.

do it (and go support your sisters on the ballot) 💪🏼💪🏽💪🏿 #govote #womenvoters #grabthembytheballot #ibelievewomen #strongertogether #reproductiverights #reproductivehealth #womenshealth #metoo #votethemout #pussygrabsback #believesurvivors #womenvote #femalehealth

text:
go out there and vote. 
i’m voting for a better country for my girls and my boy. for my nieces and nephews. 
i’m voting for a country where true equal rights are for everyone, no matter the gender, race, sexual preference, religious or political views. 
i’m voting for a country that no one is afraid to go to school, church, synagog, concert, movie theater or yoga studio.

i’m voting for a country that is compassionate to the hurting and suffering of others even if they don’t look or think like me.

i’m voting for a country that values differences and works together.

i’m voting for a country that recognizes that our actions and our way of living can affect our planet and generations to come.

i’m voting for a country that would make my parents’ sacrifices and suffering be worth it after leaving their own country and adopting this great country as theirs.

whichever is your reasoning or motive, just do it and go vote. there is so much in stake.

#imvoting #votingday #hopeful #itmatters #formykids #empoweringwomen #empowerment #girlboss #govote #votingday #yeson3

text:
day 6: a book recommended to you 
desde que me puse las "gafas moradas", soy más consciente de nuestra sociedad patriarcal y la necesidad de un cambio, así que siempre busco nuevas fuentes de información para estar al día con el feminismo y reeducar mi mentalidad (sororidad, hermanas). hace unos días, @paradalector recomendó este libro y, en cuanto vi el título, supe que lo necesitaba. y aquí lo tenéis. ¿os llama la atención? 💜✊🏻💜
.
¿de qué trata? 《tres  acontecimientos más una sentencia (el #metoo, la carta de las intelectuales francesas, la huelga feminista del 8 de marzo y la sentencia de la manada) han marcado la agenda en los últimos meses y han puesto en el punto de mira el concepto del feminismo hoy. marta sanz reflexiona acerca de lo que ello supone, cómo posicionarse ante esos hechos concretos, cómo «proteger» la lucha feminista de la simplificación y comercialización de un capitalismo que lo puede absorber todo, y piensa también sobre las cuotas y el poder, para llegar a la conclusión de que quizás lo que deba modificarse sea la noción de poder misma... una reflexión de una mujer que se pregunta, en sus actuaciones públicas y privadas, en cada gesto y cada palabra, cuál es el camino hacia la igualdad.》📖
.
#instabooks #books #bookish #bookworm #bookslover #bookstagram #bookstagramespaña #bookblogger #igbooks #libros #llibres #leer #llegir #feminism #feminismo #novemberbookchallenge

in fact, the women’s suffrage movement was a decades-long fight to win the right to vote for women in the united states. it took activists and reformers nearly 100 years to win that right, and the campaign was not easy. but on august 26, 1920, the 19th amendment to the constitution was finally ratified, enfranchising all american women and declaring for the first time that they, like men, deserve all the rights and responsibilities of citizenship.
🙏🏼
"i am well, i am happy, i am peaceful." go vote! 💙
“someone struggled for your right to vote. use it.” - susan b. anthony

text:
today, i took both my kids in the double-stroller to vote.
.
.
i voted for freedom. freedom americans are promised and freedom we inherit. freedom for others to who come to our country seeking asylum and a better life.
.
i voted for equality. equality for all races, religions, and genders (even if i don’t agree with certain lifestyles). everyone deserves the same rights no matter who they are.
.
i voted for health. for mental and physical health. for opportunities to be provided health care no matter what they can or can’t afford. for the stigma of mental health and #metoo to disappear. for those with pre-existing conditions to not be punished.
.
i voted for more voice. voice of the people. voice of those under-represented: women, minorities, lgbtq+, immigrants, millennials. i vote for bipartisanship. .
.
i voted for education. for teachers to be laid their worth. we work more than 40 hours a week and although we don’t actually teach summer months, we are still working our butts off. for every child regardless of socio-economic status or even citizen status to have a quality free education. for higher education to be cheaper and more available. for the stigma of technical and trade schools to disappear. for students to be able to learn how to learn and think for themselves and not memorize a test.
.
i vote for a greener earth. one filled with national and state parks that my children can explore. one with less pollution.
.
i vote for the right to bear arms (even though my household will never own one), but tougher restrictions and requirements on who can own what type of gun.
.
i vote for fairer taxes, lower property tax, more budget for public education, and more taxes for big businesses. for politicians being required to show their tax info if requested during campaigns.
.
i vote to support our troops, both active, retired, and discharged. i vote for support to the va.
.
i vote for mature politicians, not those who have temper tantrums on twitter.
.
i vote for the right to life. i vote for the right to worship (or not worship) how i may choose. i vote for tolerance. i vote for peace. i vote for love. i vote for what america should be.

text:
be it a saree or a dress, whatever you wear there is going to be someone out there judging your character .  we do not dress to impress or seek attention. we dress on par with comfort and choice. 
us , women, wearing a deep neck top or a short skirt triggers an adrenaline rush in men which gets out of control and leads to an act of disgust , a rape,  makes zero percent sense. imparting respect for women in men's eyes from a young age is what we need to practice. we need to educate our men like wise  putting forth the whole idea of #heforshe rather than suppressing our women.
there has been this phase on social media , a couple of months ago , i guess, when a lot of memes about the #metoo movement had been trending. i completely support the movement because it is absolutely necessary to empower the women who are not strong enough to speak freely regarding the gut wrenching incidences that have happened with them . if we cannot uplift the meek then i don't think we have rights to influence people with humour about them.
i believe shame lies in the eyes of the one who looks at you . so ladies, let's take a moment and remind ourselves that we are free to show as much skin as we like or cover our bodies as much as it pleases us. 
p.s. i drew that and i know i'm not great at it. 🙈
#feminism #feminist #women #womenempowerment #girls #strongwomen #rapevictim #rapes

text:
"the use of adjectives in the phrases "humane slaughter" and "forcible rape" promotes a conceptual mis-focusing that relativizes these acts of violence. additionally, as we ponder how the end is achieved, "forcibly", "humanely", our attention is continuously framed so that the absent referents - women, animals - do not appear. just as all rapes are forcible, all slaughter of animals for food is inhumane regardless of what it is called."
.
.
.

text:
“drc is the rape capital of the world” the un secretary-general representive on sexual violence in conflict.

the sexual violence in eastern drc is the worst in the world. some stats show that girls as young as 10 years old are raped every day & often multiple times within their lifetime. some assaults are so bad they leave them with internal injuries so severe they are close to death.

while doctors such as noble peace prize winner denis mukwege, are doing amazing work to help women they are definitely inundated & overwhelmed.

we want to create opportunities for women recovering from such violence to rebuild their lives. sometimes left with disease, pregnancy and internal injury to face, their pain is often compounded by the abandonment of their husbands leaving them without any livelihood, community or financial support. we can help by investing in their potential so they can create a new future full of hope, on the journey of recovery.

text:
rp @veganismopolitico el vegetarianismo no sirve - parte 1 
la realidad de la industria láctea 
a pesar de la creciente popularidad del veganismo, sigue habiendo un número mucho más grande de vegetarianos. la razón principal y la más común para ser vegetariano y no vegano es no querer dejar de consumir cierto producto animal, usualmente queso. 
sin embargo, si alguien es vegetariano por razones éticas, no hay razón moralmente justificable para oponerse al consumo de carne, pero no así al consumo de otros productos como lácteos, huevos y miel. 
como todas las mamíferas, las vacas sólo producen leche cuando están preñadas y después del parto. por lo tanto, las vacas están secuestradas y son inseminadas a la fuerza para que así produzcan leche. naturalmente, esta leche es para alimentar a sus terneros, pero para poder tomar su leche los granjeros separan al ternero y a su madre poco tiempo después del parto, causando una angustia tremenda e incluso ocasionando estados prolongados de depresión. mientras que las terneras usualmente se unen a su madre para la producción de leche, los terneros no producen leche y no son considerados como rentables para la producción de carne, por lo que son usualmente asesinados o enviados para producción de ternera. debido al cercano vínculo que se forma entre las vacas y sus crías, es común que estas madres griten por sus bebés perdidos, a veces hasta por días. a las vacas las ponen a sufrir este proceso agonizante de tres a cuatro veces antes de ser también asesinadas. 
no hay otra, hacete vegana/o. .
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
este martes se realiza la elección de medio mandato en estados unidos, que marca la mitad del periodo presidencial de donald trump. en estos comicios, se renueva la totalidad de la cámara de representantes, un tercio del senado y 36 gobernaciones de estado, lo que podría significar un cambio en el mapa político del país.

la votación ocurre luego de una campaña electoral que estuvo marcada por diversos temas polémicos como la migración, la violencia o el movimiento #metoo, siempre con la figura omnipresente del presidente trump.

revisa aquí los tópicos principales que se tomaron la discusión en estos meses de campaña:

trump, trump, trump

pese a que su nombre no figura en las papeletas, donald trump está, como él mismo dice, en el centro de estos comicios, que tradicionalmente se transforman en un referéndum sobre la gestión presidencial. pero, explosivo e iconoclasta, el magnate llevó esa tendencia a otro nivel. "votar por marsha es, de hecho, votar por mí", declaró trump en tennessee, junto a la candidata republicana al senado, marsha blackburn. el mandatario multiplicó sus actos de campaña hasta el último minuto, consciente de que si su partido pierde el control de congreso a manos de los demócratas, su gestión se verá paralizada.

en tanto, los demócratas esperan que la aversión que muchos electores tienen hacia el magnate provocará un aumento en la participación electoral, cuando normalmente las elecciones de medio mandato no suscitan grandes pasiones.

inmigración

el envío de militares a la frontera con méxico para evitar la "invasión" de migrantes centroamericanos que avanzan hacia estados unidos en una caravana, la promesa de acabar con el derecho de suelo, historias escabrosas de asesinos indocumentados: trump y los republicanos decidieron colocar a la inmigración en el corazón de su campaña.

pese a que su nombre no figura en las papeletas, donald trump está, como él mismo dice, en el centro de estos comicios, que tradicionalmente se transforman en un referéndum sobre la gestión presidencial. pero, explosivo e iconoclasta, el magnate llevó esa tendencia a otro nivel. "votar por marsha es, de hecho, votar por mí", declaró trump en tennessee, junto a la candidata republicana al senado, marsha blackburn. el mandatario multiplicó sus actos de campaña hasta el último minuto, consciente de que si su paido pierde el control de congreso a manos de los demócratas, su gestión se verá paralizada.

en tanto, los demócratas esperan que la aversión que muchos electores tienen hacia el magnate provocará un aumento en la paicipación electoral, cuando normalmente las elecciones de medio mandato no suscitan grandes pasiones.

inmigración

el envío de militares a la frontera con méxico para evitar la "invasión" de migrantes centroamericanos que avanzan hacia estados unidos en una caravana, la promesa de acabar con el derecho de suelo, historias escabrosas de asesinos indocumentados: trump y los republicanos decidieron colocar a la inmigración en el corazón de su campaña.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
no better time than today to share my latest blog post. 👆🏻click the link in my bio to read. 
i did it. i finally pushed the button. i've had this written for weeks, just sitting in my drafts waiting to be published, but it has taken me not just the past few weeks, rather almost 30 years to feel ready to share my stories. they've compounded on one another over time to the point that i can no longer harbor them inside. i'm ready to let go...to let them go, even though i know i'll still never feel free. but it is time. it's time for society, rules and expectations to change and that can't happen if we all remain quiet like they intended.

text:
today is the day! what are you voting for? our voice is our power. if you don’t vote, you are in effect voting for our entrenched system. i vote to create a better world for my boys; to empower women; to #resist hate, oppression and racism; to end the patriarchy; to support equal rights; to protect our planet and our children. i vote for you. 
__
took these two kiddos with me to turn in my ballet this morning. i feel an incredible responsibility to teach them how to contribute towards a better world... to be inclusive, empathetic, use their voices in situations of injustice, use their privilege to uplift those without, support and believe women always and to vote! including them today was one of many small steps i hope will teach them these values and show them that even their voice and actions matter. 
__

tout se passe sur la page facebook du même nom (ou en cherchant @recueilharcelementderue).

en tout, 17 nouvelles et donc 17 voix pour s’exprimer sur le harcèlement dans les lieux publics envers des femmes, des couples homosexuels, des victimes du racisme, etc.
des genres et des tons différents.
la version 📚 fait 350 pages 😊
bonne soirée ✨

🇬🇧 hi,
another really interesting introduction with this interview of the 10th author of the street harassment anthology 😊
this novel shows the point of views of the victim & someone who dares to help!
each author explain why they wrote it & if it’s a personal story.
there’s a facebook page for the book. 17 novellas have been selected, 17 voices for women, queer people, people of color, etc. who have been harassed.
have a great time ✨

text: in case you live under a rock...that happens to be in america...fyi it's election day‼️ if you are legally able, please, please exercise your right today if you haven't already. 🗳️📮✔️ now more than ever these #midtermelections have sooo much potential for impactful change. i 100% recognize and acknowledge that the system is broken, but that by no means means we should boycott it in protest, as the mass election apathy of 2016 proves truer by the day. representation is immensely important, so please be cogniscent of the truly hurting world we live in when electing officials to positions of power that wield the ability to orchestrate positive changes in our society. #govote for all of the americans who are daca recipients or otherwise undocumented and thus disenfranchised, for the lgbt+ community and in particular trans peoples whose rights remain threatened by the powers that be, for those who can't afford healthcare. vote for every woman and #metoo survivor constantly thrust back into trauma by the news surrounding the current administration and the kind of corrupt, misogynistic power it exemplifies, for every american not born into the same privileges you and your peers were afforded, for everyone who's lost someone to gun violence or felt the terror of the kinds of home-grown domestic terrorism encouraged by all the hateful rhetoric, & for every minority that has been or likely will be attacked by the actions and words of our callous president, vote for environmental responsibility and a fairer, more empathetic society; vote for the more hopeful america of tomorrow, not the mere tatters of its morality displayed today. 💔🌎❤️ 🗯️ if for nothing else, #vote so it's not quite so embarrassing waking up in another country and reading the latest horrific news headlines from your (& my) home every day and then having to face the general public as " the american " 🙃#makeamericalessembarrassingagain #shevotes #rockthevote #powertothepolls #voteblue 💙 #policychangeforamerica 🇺🇸 // poignant 🎨: @by.southtownstudios, @jbjork, @peopleiveloved

artists have long used their work to make statements about their beliefs, emotions or interpretation of their time. fashion, makeup, and painting are no different. in these pieces makeup artist @yvonnetheartist uses words, hashtags, and powerful phrases of the moment to evoke thought and make a statement with her artwork. thank you to our model @siennaschmidt for letting us transform you and for your patience during the detailed processes— you look stunning!  i shot two versions of this artwork. the first i thought looked a bit more timeless and fashion forward. the second a bit more aggressive. which one do you think is more effective?  strong feelings toward either?  i’m curious to see which look @yvonnetheartist chooses for her portfolio. 💋💋. hair by @auralisflores. casting by @nycbcg. #beautyeditorial #creativemakeup #makeupasart #avantgarde #politicalart #art_spotlight #makeupguru #editorialmakeup #beautyphotographer #loveislove #lgbtqia #equality #feminism #metoo #fiercewomen

text:
democracy requires showing up. 🗳🌻vote for what matters to you. to me, after living through the civil unrest and uprisings in ferguson, in my community, i couldn’t ignore being black. there were tanks rolling down streets i used to drive through and children were being tear gassed. it became such a huge part of my identity that day and i started to fear for every black man in my family. i had to vote, my life and my families life literally depended on it. i collapsed on my parents bed and cried to my dad hysterically screaming “they don’t care about you”. i’ll never forget that day that sparked this fire in me. i went back to school for the fall in california and switched my major to environmental science and policy, with a focus on environmental justice. i started spending more time outdoors and spent time as a park ranger volunteer. 
_______
i felt safe in nature, i was away from the chaos. 
________
i could breathe in deep breaths of fresh air and tune out the images of black bodies lying in the street or videos of black deaths flooding social media. the same desire i had to protect marginalized communities from harm started happening with nature. the safety it provided me and the space to practice self care was incredible, but it felt unfair. i started thinking about how other people of color just like me deserved equal access to safe natural spaces and access to clean air and fresh water resources for their overall wellbeing. they also deserved equal access to life. social justice and environmentalism are so interconnected for me. i can’t separate the two. that’s why i’m voting for a cleaner and safer future for the environment, minorities and other marginalized communities. 🌿✊🏾 vote like your life depends on it.

are you a female aged over 18? 
have you experienced unwanted or unpleasant sexual experiences? 
if so, please could you help us with our thesis research which aims to:
· explore women’s thoughts, feelings and attitudes towards unwanted or unpleasant sexual experiences. (e.g. any time someone has intentionally grabbed or touched you in a sexual way that you don't like, or you’re forced to kiss someone or do something else sexual without your explicit consent.)
· understand how you make sense of these experiences and what effect they have had on you.
· investigate the relationship between how you perceive and understand these events and your views on other things such as gender and spirituality. 
we invite you to complete an online questionnaire to tell us about your experiences (15-25 mins to complete). as a thank you for taking part, you can opt into a prize draw to win £100, £50 or £20 worth of amazon vouchers!
to take part, or find out more information please visit the link: 
https://uclpsych.eu.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/sv_8hogmtnfrmj41pt
this study has been approved by the ucl research ethics committee: project id number: 12709/001

text:
75/100 ::a vote for our voices:: my feelings on voting today lie less on party lines and more in the quest to embody our voices—the means to our mutual liberation. our system is deeply flawed, it will likely take well past our lifetime to right this ship. we have so very much to reclaim. it’s extremely hard to vote in such a broken system. today we can vote for the best of what’s in front of us, i know the options are often less then transformative—so vote with intention—using our voice to transform our world is a practice. vote to say you are awake and are witnessing our painful reality, that you are saying no to our current trajectory of violence. vote to let others know they are not alone in their persecution. vote to feel the weight of your own importance in your body. vote to validate your own meaningful existence. vote for your voice.
.
vote with heart open, with the energy of an out stretched hand: “i don’t know your experience but i see and respect you.” many have let their pain so corrode their own hearts that they have fallen far beyond reason, where a language of hatred feels comforting and familiar in their own darkness. but we must act on behalf of all of us. we are all equal.
.
we are only free when we are all free.
.
you matter, your voice matters, we are strong together—it starts here, in our waking up and forging pathways to one another. this is energy mounting—it’s an incredible and important moment in our history because in this destruction we are beginning something new, we are learning. the road ahead is long but there is joy here—in this moment, in speaking the word “vote” to one another, in this focused recognition of ourselves, we are mustering solidarity and protection. in our recognition of the deep oppression we are steeped in we choose action because we are tapped into our our sincere knowing that there is a better way. this is not a perfect process, nothing ever is, but there is joy here. #vote

text:
silence is a virtue, though not a choice
you look back at me silently, no core 
i plead you to speak, one word 
you simply stare, laid bare
white noise, keep me safe 
multiple choice, give me a sign 
i manipulate you, scroll, scroll, toll
people you may know, smile 
we can fight this tomorrow, alarm 
symptoms treated, muted
blue light, every night.

text:
words by @ascpoetry
•
"with love, from lahore. as of today, i have received 94 submissions. almost half of them had to do with abuse—physical, sexual, emotional. one particular story still follows me around. a woman, age 19, molested by her father's first cousin, age 30, while on vacation in pakistan. subsequently emotionally blackmailed & harassed by phone & threatened with suicide attempts if she ever told anyone or ceased contact. he once showed her a gun to his head over skype because she didn't send videos. it was abuse that followed her across continents. for years. that should make your bones tremble. pakistani culture often encourages victims to seek relief from pain only in god, islam, and the quran instead of therapy or legal justice. and for that reason, pakistan doesn't have very many christine blasey ford's or #metoo campaigns. instead, the author of this submission battled bulimia as a result of the abuse. she has privately and independently coped, as many woc end up doing, citing leaving her home to study abroad as an important component of her healing. this poem is for her & all the other ones just like her. an explanation as to why so many victims never come forward. we understand. we still believe you. #withlovefromlahore"
•
•
•

"i am in awe of the remarkable women – and men – who fought so hard for so long to give women a seat at the table and a place at the polls. their work not only inspires me, it also fills me with a sense of obligation to take full advantage of the opportunities and rights they made possible for all of us. i need to vote. we all do.

in this era of #metoo, it’s easy to succumb to the sheer exhaustion of trying to change the world or even make a difference. but as i think about the people who, for decades, mobilized, marched, rallied, advocated, petitioned and wrestled for women’s right to vote, i realize i cannot ignore the fundamental right and responsibility they secured.
get out and vote. your voice matters.

text:
when my alma mater asked me to speak to the undergrads i considered a number of different topics that i could share with the students and faculty. 
and then i looked at the date they had booked me for: november 6. the day that our neighbours to the south, and a formidable presence on the world stage, are having their midterm elections. and i knew what i needed to say. 
so today we are talking about meeting god, not in the halls of power and prestige, but in the margins with those who have been overlooked, excluded, disposed of and silenced by systemic structures of inequality. and when we step into the margins together we experience a communion that is hard to describe, that reveals how god never stops working in the midst of our suffering and that jesus came to redeem every broken thing. 
get ready y’all. it’s gonna be a good one!

text:
so, i cried while i was voting today. it was empowering to cast my votes for so many women and just the very act of voting is empowering for me, specifically, for many reasons. and, yes, i still consider it a privilege to vote. in many ways i’m sad and disappointed in this country and in many ways i am proud to be an american. so many people fought for my right to vote and, in casting my votes today, i showed them honor and respect. i also showed myself honor and respect by voting because i had the choice to do so and i had the choice to vote for whoever i wanted and that's empowering. i’m not here to argue about whether my vote matters - there is something to say on either side of that topic. i voted for many reasons today, but especially because i have a choice, and my choice matters. and, i can't say enough that it was very empowering for me to cast my vote for so many women! let’s all keep on fighting the good fight!
✔️

text:
since we are all getting personal about what we vote for, i have compiled a short list:
1. fair, equal and affordable healthcare access. 
2. the rights of our people, including trans, lgbtq, people of color, native people, #metoo, immigrants, sex workers, people practicing literally any other religion than catholicism/christianity. 
3. clean water. (why the is this still an issue?)
4. comprehensive gun laws cause ya know, kids shouldn't be killed while trying to get an education. 
5. better education for all, regardless of community economic status. and furthermore....
6. better wages for all, but especially: teachers, folks working min wage jobs.
7. continued division of church & state. 
8. reproductive protection because we know family planning drastically changes the course of a woman's life. 
9. voting representation in the house and senate for dc residents. washington, dc's 600k+ residents don't have any voting power on the matters that are affecting our country. 
and finally, 10. i'm voting for people who unify our country. there is no more room for folks screaming hate into our hearts, labeling "the other" as "the enemy of the people". #gtfo

text:
no es la primera vez que la actriz estadounidense pamela anderson (@pamelaanderson), fija su posición acerca de la polémica que gira en torno a las denuncias por abusos sexuales en hollywood y en esta oportunidad aseguró que las mujeres denunciantes del #metoo carecen de “sentido común“. .
.
la modelo que fue portada de la revista playboy 15 veces, en una entrevista con el programa australiano 60 minutos, afirmó ser feminista pero que dicho movimiento “paraliza a los hombres”, “#metoo es demasiado para mí. lo siento, probablemente me maten por decir eso”, expresó la estrella de 51 años al periodista liam bartlett. .
.
anderson señaló que las “reuniones de negocios” que mencionan las actrices que denunciaron que a el productor harvey weinstein de prometerle un posible trabajo para acosarlas en hoteles, se pueden evitar. .
.

text:
we are so incredibly excited to introduce you to it’s h.e.r. business! we’re a social enterprise whose aim is to create beautiful, costumed-made jackets for a cause. every jacket purchased will benefit a woman or child affected by issues such as poverty, education and sexual assault/ abuse. by following our page, you have shown a commitment to addressing these national issues and with that we’d like to thank you for joining our cause.

speaking of supporting our mission, we are hosting our very first launch party—and you’re invited! pictured above is our keynote speaker for our launch, eleana frangedis. •••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••• a little about elena is that she is miss teen america (2012), a graduate from florida atlantic university, a motivational speaker & a sisterhood activist. she is on a mission to bring the essence of sisterhood back into play amongst women in sororities. she is passionate about uniting women with similar values, mindsets & goals, which in turn, helps each individual woman achieve her goals at a much more accelerated rate. “i am so excited to be part of an event that supports women at the most pivotal time in their life.” •••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••• click the website listed in our bio for more details regarding our trunk show launch. we promise you won’t want to miss this event. let the countdown begin!

#socialenterprise #womenempowerment #youth #education #poverty #metoo #launch #trunkshow #imwithher #helpingeveryonerebuild

text: today was a great day! i started it by going to my gyno. (let’s be real i don’t actually enjoy that part.) but what i do love is that i, as woman, get to decide what i want to do with my body and who gets to care for it. i make the decisions about what birth control i take to benefit my needs....whatever those may be. i am in control of my body.  i left there to go vote. where i watched dozens of young people pour in the door (honestly mostly women). and i thought to myself, there’s hope. there are others out there who care. i voted today for my rights. i voted for my sister’s rights. i voted for her wife’s rights. i voted for my niece’s rights. i voted for the future.  i find it fitting that rbg holds my sticker. she and my niece watch over my desk every day and remind me to keep looking forward and be the change. 👩🏻‍⚖️🚺✊🏼👭🇺🇸❤️💙 #ivoted #gofuckingvote #bethechange #rbgforlife #mybodymychoice #metoo

text:
on this first #electionday when i am an ex-pat, i am thinking about the #feminineuprising. i am thinking about a million women stepping up to say #metoo. i am thinking about how all this storytelling has awakened us, how everyone says there will be hell to pay on this election. i agree, it is time for all of us to stop sleepwalking, but i don’t believe that the revolution will, to borrow a phrase, be televised. 
____
in honor of the silent revolution, i wrote a blog post all about this. when the cable stations finally shut down from all the election reporting, perhaps you’ll take a read (check my bio for the link). _____
i used to think the revolution would happen through mass protests. we would clog the streets holding signs and shouting so that no business as usual could happen. they would have to listen. they would have to respond to our demands. but no -- we have overtired babies and mortgages to pay. and besides, there is no “they” who is not “me.” _____
i’ve stopped waiting for someone else to give me the code word. i’ve stopped putting stock in poster paint. i’ve started to do this on my own terms. 
_____
my revolution has led me to many choices, many places. this year, my revolution found me driving in a rusty van down a mexican highway, nursing my toddler to sleep on my lap and trusting very, very deeply. my revolution finds me waking up at dawn every day to meditate under the careful watch of venus, and then dancing in the blood-red rivers at kali ma’s feet as the sun cuts pink across the sky. my revolution finds me licking every single drop of juice from an orange, just picked from a tree and sliced open with a razor sharp stainless steel knife that i clean with the same reverence a warrior might give to her sword. 
_____
my revolution has me doing a million things every day, and you may never know about any of them. 
____
check out my words at sevamama.com/blog. and if you want to work with me to find your #intuitive revolution/evolution, send me a dm.

text: as a young woman living in america, i have never been so concerned for my future as i am right now. it seems every day that someone is trying to take away the rights that so many amazing, courageous women before me fought for. i will not let their strife go down in vain. i will do whatever i can to try to take control of this hell ride that has been the last 2 years. before you convince yourself that your vote doesn't matter, please think of the millions of women on medicaid who will soon have their health care stripped from them. please think of the fact that the mother fuckers in legislature are still trying to tell us what the fuck we can do with our bodies. please think of the sexual assault victims who still are being shamed away from pursuing prosecution against their attackers. please think of your sister, your mother, your daughter, and every woman that you love. your vote matters. so much.

text:
this is what 30 minutes of sleep looks like these days. 
ok so i don’t look like a beauty queen.... however, this mornings been a total win . 
crayyyyy right?? i got to bed super late, as soon as my head hit the pillow my little started throwing up.  that continued all night and morning. 
miraculously, this morning actually has been super productive, and my other two got to school on time, and we weren’t even rushing out the door ! 
i can’t help but think what this would have looked like 11 months ago for me. 
i would have been frantic in the morning trying to get the boys to school, probably almost over slept.  then, i would have been crashing on the couch for the entire school day with ethan, barely functioning, getting inwardly frustrated every time ethan needed me to get up and get him something.  not frustrated at him, but just because i was so over tired and crabby. 
patience would be running super thin. 
i would have been thinking how this freaking sucks so bad, doing this all alone, with no help, no spouse, out in the sticks as a single mom and no family to help. 
which then, would have spiraled into anger, and bitterness, because this is the reality of my life. 
ok so my hairs still unbrushed, i’m in sweats and without makeup... don’t worry teeth are brushed. i’m a freak about that ! 🤣

but hey... i don’t feel like my body is shutting down!  and i have the energy to take care of my sweet little ethan, without being overly tired and crabby. 
i have patients and i have energy. 
i even made some homemade treats with nutrient dense goodies to help his belly and throat! 
i could never put a price tag on how i feel.

there is a better way to live ♥️ y’all •

••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
as a little boy, with a work-a-holic father, i was raised by my mother, my older sister, my grand parents, my female school teachers and my female sunday school teachers. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
i grew up learning that my worth was derived by my ability to please the women in my life. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
my lack of a present male role model took its toll. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
i pretended to be masculine, pretended to be confident and pretended i knew what it meant to be a man. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
in reality, i was scared shitless following the examples of those masculine role models i saw on tv & in movies. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
heman, conan the barbarian  superman, the flash, batman, william wallace, the gladiator, james bond, king leonidas to name a few. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
through my greatest failures i learned to redefine what it means for me to be an evolved and conscious man.
••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
yes, i still get triggered and choose to shut down my emotions at times however, it’s a daily practice where i strive to continuously improve. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
for me, being a man means stepping into your greatness and slaying dragons 🐉 of your fears everyday. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
being a man is showing up for your queen, not attempting to fix her problems while being her sounding board and rock when the storms roar around you. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
being a man is being clear, constant and committed to your life mission. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
being a man is being a role model to your children. teaching them how to respect women, other men, themselves and to be stewards of humanity; leaving this world better than they found it. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
being a man is taking care of your health so that you have no excuses as to why you’re not able to participate 100% in the lives of your loved ones. ••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
there are so many other ways the “masculine man 2.0” shows up and its time we as men, step up and redefine what it means to be a man in this day and age.
••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
it’s time to be powerfully present mentors to the next generation.
••⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
our sons, daughters, wives and partners need us more now than ever!

text:
i voted. i was not planning to post about it but, again, i encountered the man who tries to intimidate the voters at my polling place. last year, i went in, told, precinct worker came out, he claimed he was far enough away and she went back in. i reported him and nothing happened.

this time, i just unloaded on him myself. regular followers know i live in the calvinist dutch neighborhood and i vote in one of their churches. they aren’t used to anyone, specially some woman, going ballistic. when i came out, he was nowhere to be seen. i’m sure he thought i was going to tell on him again. i’ll admit, part of me feared he was locking and loading in a car somewhere, but i guess i gotta be willing to fully take my stand. yikes. 
i was so happy to see the turnout and that it was far more plentiful and diverse than the time of which we shall not speak. #249 at 9:20am. 👍🏿✊🏻👊🏼👆🏼🤘💙
.

.
.

text:
being a therapist means hearing people’s lived experiences day in and day out. part of our job is to be an advocate for all the clients we treat. i would argue this role means we are responsible for being socially conscious and in being a force for the rights of all humans- not just our clients. .
which is why i am choosing not to stay silent about my political views on my business platform- it is impossible to be a social worker and to ignore what’s going on in our society. it would be irresponsible to stay silent. .
i vote today for trans and lgbtq rights, for people of color, for immigrants, to put women in politics. i vote for women’s right to choose, for keeping our world healthy, and to keep our communities safe from hate. .
please get out and vote today. vote like your life depends on it. for many, it does.
.

i wanted to remind y’all of a few things:
-polls are open til 7pm in tx
-you should get out and vote even if we aren’t voting for the same candidate because that’s your right and it’s how democracy works
-i urge you, however, to do your own research and vote for a candidate you can stand behind and live with the fact that you supported
-realize that “voting because it doesn’t affect me” is a privilege not many people have and it’s just not ~cool~
-if you’re in line by 7pm you legally have the right to cast your vote
-double check your ballot before submitting it, especially if you vote a straight ticket, don’t wanna look down and accidentally see a mixup by the machine and cast your vote for ted cruz... i mean, whatever candidate you don’t support
-you are legally allowed to leave work on election day in tx for however long it takes to cast your vote
-a lot is at stake this election (and every election), so vote with intersectionality in mind. keep immigrants’ rights, lgbtq rights, women’s rights, etc. all in mind when you push that vote button!
-text your friends and family and make sure they went out and did the damn thing!
-if you need to find your nearest polling location click the link in my bio!

text:
today is election day. i am voting to ensure future generations will have the strength, courage, and backbone to not shame, discredit or not believe survivors of sexual assault, abuse and misconduct. to ensure that our leaders from the top down do not treat women like pieces of meat, to be mocked, abused, sexualized, and laughed at. as a survivor of sexual assault, i wear this shirt in solidarity for all people who have been abused. this shirt arrived at my door with a cut slashed in the front, slightly imperfect, a little scarred, and bit different from the rest. after a feeling of slight annoyance to not receive a perfect new one, i realized the shirt came exactly how it should. the shirt, like me, may be a little worn, imperfect, slightly scarred, but it shouldn’t be thrown out and tossed aside. my slight imperfections, my past, has fueled me to be stronger, more passionate, and emboldened to make change now. what happened to me as a teenager, will never release itself from my consciousness as i go through my everyday life. as much as you move on, you can never erase the past. i pray future generations will know how to protect themselves, how to respect each other so this gross abuse of women will become a thing of the past. until it does, we will fight. please vote today, for whatever you care about in your life. it’s your right, your privilege, and your duty as a person lucky enough to live in this incredible country. #timesup #metoo #believewomen #believesurvivors #vote 
https://www.ibelievewomen.com
all proceeds from the sale of these shirts go to organizations working every day on the front lines, protecting and fighting for survivors.

text:
imagine being able to hold this administration accountable and actually make progress when it comes to affordable health care, the rights of immigrants and refugees, the urgent problem of climate change—i could go on and on.

for the past two years, we've watched this administration attack and undermine our democratic institutions and values. today, we say enough. 
but we won't just vote against radicalism, bigotry, and corruption today. 
we'll vote for fantastic candidates all over the country—including a historic number of women—who want to raise wages, fight for justice, and help more people get health care. 
if they win, they’ll do great things for america. let's exercise our birthright as americans today, put those people in office, and continue the hard work of saving our democracy. 
it'll take all of us. happy election day.

secretary @hillaryclinton

no one can afford to sit on the sidelines.
too much is at stake. make a plan to cast your vote today.

have friends or family in any of these states?

please share and let them know that they can register to vote in person on #electionday.

if you don't know where your polling place is, go to www.iwillvote.com

find your closest swing district with @swing left, and let's get to work: http://bit.ly/joinhillary

@votolatino & @lyft are providing free rides to the polls in #arizona, #california, #colorado, #georgia, #kansas, #florida, #nevada, #newmexico, #texas, & #wisconsin.

spread the word: to request a ride, text votevl to 73179.

you can also help cover rides here: https://secure.actblue.com/…/ms_lyft-rides-to-polls_vl_q420…

question about voting: 833.336-vote

if your rights are being violated:

election protection hotline:
866.687.8683

department of justice voting rights hotline: 800.253.3931

text:
i don’t regret the windy path, the healing, or the hard lessons that molded me into the woman that i am now. i am proud of this version of me. however, if i could go back and tell my 19-21 year old self one thing, it would be: stop numbing your trauma with alcohol. stop drinking because your only reason is "other people are" and definitely stop when it begins to make you feel sad.
.
when i was in syracuse last week, i bumped into someone who hasn’t seen me since i graduated, since i was in that phase of life where i subconsciously numbed. in the conversation, she made a joke about how i used to be able to "drink other people under the table". not her fault for saying that because those were my actions and i grudgingly own them to be mine to be responsible for.
.
and then she looked at me and with a startled look in her eyes said: “you’ve lost weight”.
.
side note — this is not a compliment unless you know a human is actively in a weight-loss journey. also… why do we still live in a society in which we verbalize thoughts about our fellow women’s bodies?
.
side note v.2 — i’ve actually gained weight since starting my journey with weight lighting. i am the heaviest i’ve ever weighed. though that truly doesn’t matter…. what she was referring to was the beer weight and inflammation i used to hold in my face.
.
in the moment, i felt all the trauma i collected through my actions. i felt the struggles that used to be truly heavy burdens. and i realized and acknowledged that the assault was not the only trauma that occurred to my physical body at syracuse.
.
and that is okay, for our traumas and our healing make up who we are. these little moments that shine light on them are opportunities to heal further. they are invitations that we have indeed made progress. they are shimmers of truth and reminders that it is normal to struggle with being freaking human during times of hardship.
.
to my trauma body, i see you. i honor you. and i thank you for leading me to a path of continuous healing. and alcohol, i’m thankful i no longer lean on you, that i can feel all my feelings in full force and still be whole.

text:
✨natalie moore: why is ida’s moment happening right now?
✨michelle duster: it’s a combination of the current demonization of the media, the #metoo movement, and state sponsored violence. people want to know how she did what she did during a similar political climate. ✨eve ewing: it’s 2018 and black women are still being marginalized on the fronts of both racial justice and gender equality. ida b. wells insisted on the fullness of both identities. ✨nikole hannah-jones: in elementary school, it was black history month and they put 5 black people up and she was one of them! but i never understood what she did. it wasn’t until i was in college and decided to be a journalist that i found her memoir. even if you don’t think your work as a journalist will change the world you still have to document.

text:
"i am in awe of the remarkable women – and men – who fought so hard for so long to give women a seat at the table and a place at the polls. their work not only inspires me, it also fills me with a sense of obligation to take full advantage of the opportunities and rights they made possible for all of us. i need to vote. we all do.

in this era of #metoo and #timesup and #neveragain, it’s easy to succumb to the sheer exhaustion of trying to change the world or even make a difference. but as i think about the people who, for decades, mobilized, marched, rallied, advocated, petitioned and wrestled for women’s right to vote, i realize i cannot ignore the fundamental right and responsibility they secured.

this isn’t a partisan plea. if you are happy with the path we are traveling: vote to sustain it. if you are not happy, vote to change it. just vote." - lynn branigan, president & ceo, @sherunsitorg 📷: @riflepaperco

text:
first, let me say…internally scream, me too. i stand along side with survivors and victims of #sexualviolence. because i am both. i experience and still feel as #victim; and as #survivor. 🔻
i sincerely and lovingly apologize if this question caused/triggered/surfaced any pain/discomfort or past trauma. 🔻it did. for #metoo 🔻but the question was formulated, and sat in stillness with me during the emotionally and mentally brutal confirmation of #kavanaugh as a supreme court justice. the question still sits with me now. and haunts me. it haunts me as did the questions from my past’s insecurities, doubts and confusion with if i had provoked, helped, assisted, or caused my own sexual assaults. to excuse and think, during and after, the offender was unaware of what they were doing…because i hadn’t verbally or physically resisted enough, or at all…began to haunt me. again. 🔻
today, although my mind and body still remember and can experience that fear and doubt, i know better. i’ve learned. better. those ‘some days’ of #misunderstanding my sexual assaults eventually turned into most days. most days into #everyday. and #today, i am confidently #educated, #informed and #validated. today, i am secured and established and experienced with my space and #demands and #expectations, as a #woman. 🔻but, today. i’m raising #boys. 2 boys. i’m a #motherofsons. and that question…can #rape be an accident? isn’t an absolute no for me. and it won’t be until i know what my children’s experience with #consent and valuing girls will be; what their answer to this question will firmly be. and what i know it needs to be—absolutely. no. 🔻for far too many, the answer to this question is debatable; when there should be no debate in sexual violence. even with an absence of verbal and physical resistance, sexually violent acts should not be honored with political subjection. to dismiss any act of sexual violence as an accident; is to base yourself, your mindset, your choices and your power in gender inequality. the #objectification of girls’ and women’s value; and the subjugation of women to #victimblaming—is no accident. rape, is no accident. #wetoo #titleix #itsonus #betsydevos #believesurvivors

text:
dramaten uppmärksammar årsdagen av skådespelaruppropet.

den 8 november 2017 samlades, i ett gemensamt upprop i svenska dagbladet, 703 skådespelare och berättade om sexuella övergrepp och trakasserier som de har bevittnat eller utsatts för i film- och teaterbranschen. uppropet, kallat #tystnadtagning, kom i svallvågorna av #metoo och fick ett stort genomslag både i sverige och utomlands. efter det följde en lång rad upprop från andra branscher. och nu – den 8 november 2018 – uppmärksammar dramaten årsdagen av #tystnadtagning genom en premiär på lilla scenen, ett scensamtal i dramatenbaren och en öppen premiärskål i marmorfoajén.

19.00–20.30 premiär who’s afraid of jenny wilson?, lilla scenen
19.30–20.15 samtal kvinnan på teatern, dramatenbaren
20.30–22.00 öppen premiärskål där eirik stubø, teaterchef, hälsar välkommen och sara danius, ledamot i dramatens styrelse, håller tal, marmorfoajén 
mer info och biljetter på dramaten.se.
